definition.value: potential energy that binds an electron to its atom or molecule.
potential energy that binds nucleons to form the atomic nucleus (and nuclear reactions).

value.value: Potential energy due to the energy of the gluon-mediated field of the strong force, binding quarks together into hadrons.

definition.value: potential energy due to the deformation of a material (or its container) exhibiting a restorative force.
Wave energy which inheres in an elastic material and is realised when a deformational wave passes through that material.
Mechanical wave energy which is realised when an acoustic wave propagates through a material.
Potential energy which is stored in the fields of propagated by electromagnetic radiation.
potential energy due to an object's rest mass.
Kinetic energy which is realised through the microscopic motion of particles.
A form of disordered mechanical energy.
Mechanical wave energy which inheres in an atmosphere and is realised during an atmospheric wind.
Thermal energy which propagates through a solid (typically rocky) astronomical body.
Often, this term is used specifically for thermal energy spreading from heat sources (e.g. magma chambers, the planetary core) within the Earth. However, it is also used for extraterrestrial bodies.
A power station which burns a fossil fuel such as coal, natural gas, or petroleum to produce electricity.
Coal heated in the absence of air.
A biogeochemical cycle which has oxygen as participant.
An environment which is determined by an anatomical entity.
An environmental system determined by an intestine.
An environment determined by an area or zone of skin tissue.

value.value: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted at wavelengths and frequencies which travel exclusively in a line-of-sight fashion and which may produce molecular rotation and torsion on contact with matter.

definition.value: This definition focuses on the properties of microwaves rather than their wavelength or frequency limits. Considerable ambiguity exists around the wavelength and frequency thresholds of microwaves. The ISO 21348 definition bounds these waves at 1 mm and 15 mm, with frequencies between 100 GHz and 0.225 GHz.

value.value: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted at wavelengths ranging from millimetre to kilometer scales.

definition.value: As with microwaves, considerable variation exists in the delimitation of frequency and wavelength thresholds for radiowaves. The ISO 21348 standard allows a wavelength range of 0.10 mm to 100 m and a frequency range of 300 GHz to 3 MHz. However, much lower thresholds also exist.

value.value: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted when molecules change their rotational-vibrational movements, usually at wavelengths between 760 nm and 1 mm.
A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted at wavelengths between 380 nm and 760 nm.
A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted at wavelengths between 10 nm and 400 nm.
A radiation process during which penetrating electromagnetic radiation is emitted by high-energy electrons as they fall into a lower state of energy.
A radiation process during which penetrating electromagnetic radiation is emitted from the radioactive decay (gamma decay) of atomic nuclei.
A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted with sufficient energy to disrupt molecular bonds or alter the electron number of atoms.
